---
/**
 * Experiment 006: Fourier Epicycles
 *
 * A visual demonstration of the Discrete Fourier Transform. Draw any shape,
 * decompose it into frequency components, then reconstruct it using stacked
 * rotating circles (epicycles). Each circle's radius = a frequency's amplitude,
 * its rotation speed = the frequency index. The tip of the last circle traces
 * the original shape.
 *
 * WHAT IS THE FOURIER TRANSFORM?
 * ==============================
 * Any periodic signal — a sound wave, a heartbeat, a closed curve — can be
 * decomposed into a sum of sines and cosines at different frequencies. This
 * is the Fourier Transform's core insight, published by Joseph Fourier in 1807.
 *
 * Intuitively: every complex wave is a choir of simple waves singing together.
 * The Fourier Transform tells you who is singing (which frequencies), how loud
 * each voice is (amplitude), and when each voice starts (phase).
 *
 * WHAT IS A FREQUENCY COMPONENT?
 * ==============================
 * Each component is defined by three numbers:
 *   - Frequency (k): how many full rotations per cycle. k=1 goes around once,
 *     k=5 goes around five times. Negative k means counter-clockwise.
 *   - Amplitude (|X_k|): the SIZE of the circle — how much this frequency
 *     contributes to the shape. Large amplitude = dominant feature.
 *   - Phase (arg(X_k)): the STARTING ANGLE of the rotation — where on the
 *     circle we begin at t=0. Phase determines alignment.
 *
 * WHAT THE COMPLEX EXPONENTIAL MEANS GEOMETRICALLY
 * =================================================
 * The DFT uses e^(-2πi·k·n/N). What does this mean?
 *
 * Euler's formula: e^(iθ) = cos(θ) + i·sin(θ)
 *
 * So e^(iθ) is a POINT ON THE UNIT CIRCLE at angle θ. As θ increases, the
 * point ROTATES around the circle. e^(-2πi·k·n/N) rotates k times as n goes
 * from 0 to N-1. It's a spinning arrow (phasor) in the complex plane.
 *
 * The DFT multiplies each sample point by this spinning arrow and sums up.
 * If the signal has energy at frequency k, the products align constructively
 * (they point the same way and add up). If not, they cancel out (pointing in
 * all directions, summing to ~zero). This is correlation detection: "does the
 * signal contain this frequency?"
 *
 * WHY SORTING BY AMPLITUDE WORKS
 * ==============================
 * Sorting components by amplitude (largest circle first) means we add the
 * most important features first. With just 1-2 epicycles, you get the rough
 * outline. Adding more refines the details. This is exactly how compression
 * works: keep the big coefficients, discard the small ones.
 *
 * For smooth shapes, amplitude drops off quickly — a few circles suffice.
 * For shapes with sharp corners (like a square wave), amplitude drops slowly
 * and you see the GIBBS PHENOMENON: overshooting "ears" near the corners
 * that persist no matter how many terms you add. The Gibbs overshoot is always
 * about 9% of the jump height — a fundamental limit of Fourier approximation.
 *
 * WHY THIS WORKS FOR ANY SHAPE
 * ============================
 * The DFT doesn't care what shape you draw. It treats the (x, y) coordinates
 * as a complex number x + iy at each sample point. Any closed curve in 2D
 * is a periodic complex-valued signal, and the DFT decomposes it into its
 * constituent rotations. This universality is why the Fourier Transform
 * appears everywhere in science and engineering.
 *
 * REAL-WORLD USES
 * ===============
 * - JPEG compression: DCT (a cousin of DFT) decomposes image blocks into
 *   frequency components; discard the tiny ones → smaller file
 * - Audio processing: FFT identifies which notes are playing in real time
 * - MRI machines: measure frequency-domain data directly, then inverse-FFT
 *   to reconstruct the spatial image of your body
 * - Signal filtering: remove specific frequencies (noise, hum) by zeroing
 *   their Fourier coefficients
 * - Telecommunications: OFDM (used in WiFi, 4G/5G) encodes data on many
 *   frequency carriers simultaneously using FFT/IFFT
 */
---

<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>006 — Fourier Epicycles | Generative Lab</title>
  <style>
    *, *::before, *::after { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }

    body {
      background: #0a0a0f;
      color: #e0e0e0;
      font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', 'Consolas', monospace;
      overflow: hidden;
      height: 100dvh;
